04340nam a22005175i 9780773563643DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19921992xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735636437 a10.1515/97807735636432doi  a(DE-B1597)656740  a(OCoLC)732601029  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJL193bS75 1992eb 7aPOL0400002bisacsh04a324.971/06471 aJohnston, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLetting the People Decide :bDynamics of a Canadian Election /cRichard Johnston, Andre Blais. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1992] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue: Gambling on the People -- tThe Campaign Roller-Coaster -- tThe Electoral Background: History and Geography -- tThe Background of the Party System: Party Identification, Social Structure, and Sentiment -- tThe Campaign in the Media: Illusion as Reality? -- tFree Trade and the Control of the Agenda -- tTraits, Debates, and Leaders' Fates -- tExpectations: Self-Fulfilling Prophecies? -- tAsking the Right Question: The Campaign Agenda, Priming, and the Vote -- tEpilogue: Party Strategy and the Dynamics of Campaigns -- tAppendix A: The 1988 Canadian Election Study Sample -- tAppendix B: Two Notes on Estimation -- tAppendix C: Coding of Media Quantities -- tAppendix D: Comparing Questions about the FTA -- tAppendix E: Measurement of Expectations -- tAppendix F: Selected CES 1988 Survey Items -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe authors have based the book primarily on data derived from the 1988 Canadian Election Study, for which they were co-investigators. The survey was a "rolling cross-section": a daily tracking of the campaign designed explicitly to monitor electoral dynamics. The multivariate techniques commonly involved in the analysis of campaign data are presented here in an accessible way, as graphs rather than tables. Videotapes of prime time news analyses on CBC, CTV, and SRC outlets, as well as some newspaper commentaries, have been integrated into the survey. This information is contrasted with an analysis of electoral dynamics based on one hundred years of census and electoral data. The authors make a variety of significant arguments about the historical and political basis of the parties' eventual positions on the issue of free trade, the overriding importance of that issue to the 1988 election, the roles of the party leaders, and, perhaps most important, the political impact of campaigns, especially of debates and media coverage. Letting the People Decide brings the study of Canadian parties into the analytical mainstream even as it supplies a new interpretation of a century of elections.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh1 aBlais, Andre, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356364340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773563643423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773563643/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles